#Reference: https://www.r-bloggers.com/scatter-plot-matrices-in-r/


#Scatter Plot with Correlation and P Value
panel.cor <- function(x, y, digits = 2, cex.cor=.8, ...)
{ 
  
  #Plotting Regression Line
  reg1 <- lm(x~y)
  abline(reg1,col = "gray60")
  
  usr <- par("usr"); on.exit(par(usr))
  par(usr = c(0, 1, 0, 1))
  # correlation coefficient
  r <- cor(x, y)
  txt <- format(c(r, 0.123456789), digits = digits)[1]
  txt <- paste("r= ", txt, sep = "")
  text(0.5, 0.6, txt)

  # p-value calculation
  p <- cor.test(x, y)$p.value
  txt2 <- format(c(p, 0.123456789), digits = digits)[1]
  txt2 <- paste("p= ", txt2, sep = "")
  if(p<0.01) txt2 <- paste("p= ", "<0.01", sep = "") 
  text(0.5, 0.4, txt2)
}

pairs(oj_subset[,-1], upper.panel = panel.cor,col="blue",pch=20)

## create some data for prediction, using the data.frame function
## note the care in specifying brand factor (levels must match original data)
## we don't need all variables in oj; just those used as covariates in reg.
newdata=data.frame(price=rep(4,3), 
    brand=factor(c("tropicana","minute.maid","dominicks"),levels=levels(oj$brand)))
